**Method 1**

This was the first and simplest method that popped into my head. Copy the second array into the "empty" half of the first array, and then sort it. Around 56ms (~80%) run time.

Simply using .sort() isn't enough as it will sort lexigraphically (worth remembering), so we have to pass it a custom sort function.

```
var merge = function(nums1, m, nums2, n) {

    if (!n) return;    

    for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        nums1[m+i] = nums2[i];
    }

    nums1.sort(function (a,b) {
        return a - b;
    });

}; 
```

**Method 2**

This is essentially a dual pointer approach. Make a copy of nums1, and then step through the nums1 copy and nums2, from the front, adding whichever is smallest back into nums1.

This obviously will increase memory use, but produces 52ms runtime (i.e 100%).

```
var merge = function(nums1, m, nums2, n) {

    if (n == 0) return;

    let nums1copy = [...nums1], mm = 0, nn = 0;

    for (let i = 0; i < (m+n); i++) {
        //Is it smaller, or have we run out of the second list?
        if ( (nums1copy[mm] < nums2[nn] && mm < m) || nn >= n ) {
            nums1[i] = nums1copy[mm];
            mm++;
        } else {
            nums1[i] = nums2[nn];
            nn++;
        }   
    }
}
```

**Method 3**

This method uses no additional memory and retains the 52ms (100%) runtime.

The biggest problem with starting from the front, is that you run into trouble with overwriting values etc. and it likely won't work.

This method starts from the back - where our "empty" spaces are. Similar to method 2, we are basically keeping two pointers, but starting at the back and looking for the bigger of the two numbers instead of the smaller.

The code would be a lot more legible if we simply "let i = m + n" but I quite liked the zero memory consumption of this approach.

```
var merge = function(nums1, m, nums2, n) {
    //we don't want the length, we want the start position of the final elements
    m--;
    n--;

    while (m + n >= -1) {
        //If bigger, or nothing left in nums2, copy it over
        if ( (nums1[m] > nums2[n] ) || n < 0) {
            nums1[m + n + 1] = nums1[m];
            m--;
        } else {
            nums1[m + n + 1] = nums2[n];
            n--;
        }
    }
}
```

