solutions.content:
The idea here is to initialize two pointers(m&n) and point them to the end of both the arrays...

Now, we also track the position where new element is to be inserted (k)

Now, we traverse both the arrays from end and compare the value of elements at intex m and n.
Since the elements in both the arrays are sorted, we follow the following rules...
If element at m is greater than n then we place it in kth index and decrement both k and m...
If element at n is greater than m, then we place it in kth index and decrement both k and n...

**Pls upvote this thread if you found this solution helpful.**

```
class Solution {
public:
    void merge(vector<int>& nums1, int m, vector<int>& nums2, int n) {
		//Size of nums1 including 0's
        int k=m+n-1;

		//Both the pointers to point at last index
        m--;
        n--;

        while(m>=0 && n>=0) {
			//Comparing the values and adjusting the k value accordingly
            if(nums1[m]>nums2[n]) nums1[k--]=nums1[m--];
            else nums1[k--]=nums2[n--];
        }

		//It might happen that elements of second array are smaller than smallest element of first array
        while(n>=0) nums1[k--]=nums2[n--];

		//We need not cover the otherwise case of first array elements begin smaller, because they are already in first half of the array
    }
};
```

