Note: I'll be using 0 based indexing everywhere in this post.

Let's start with the example k = 2, prices = [3,2,6,5,0,3].

Here, the answer is 7, buying on day 1 and selling on day 2,for a profit of 4 and then buying on day 4 and selling on day 5, for a profit of 3.

Mathematically, this can be represented as : (3 - 0) + (6 - 2),
which can be translated to  3 - (0 - (6 -2)).

Thus, a general expression can be written as SP<sub>1</sub> - (CP<sub>1</sub>  - (SP<sub>0</sub>  - CP<sub>0</sub> ))
,where SP<sub>i</sub>  is the selling price of the stock for the ith transaction, and CP<sub>i</sub>  is the cost price for the i<sup>th</sup> transaction.

It's apparent that initially we have to minimize CP<sub>0</sub>, then maximize the expression (SP<sub>0</sub>  - CP<sub>0</sub> ), which is the profit for the 0th transaction, then minimize (CP<sub>1</sub>  - (SP<sub>0</sub> ,CP<sub>0</sub> )),  and ultimately maximize SP<sub>1</sub>  - (CP<sub>1</sub>  - (SP<sub>0</sub> ,CP<sub>0</sub> )) to get the optimal result.

A general expression for k terms can be written as thus : SP<sub>k-1</sub>  - (CP<sub>k-1</sub>  - (SP<sub>k-2</sub>  - CP<sub>k-2</sub> -(.....-(SP<sub>1</sub>  - (CP<sub>1</sub>  - (SP<sub>0</sub>  - CP<sub>0</sub> ))))))

It's important to note that (CP<sub>i</sub>  - (SP<sub>i-1</sub>  - CP<sub>i-1</sub> -(.....-(SP<sub>1</sub>  - (CP<sub>1</sub>  - (SP<sub>0</sub>  - CP<sub>0</sub> )))))) is the overall cost price for the i<sup>th</sup> transaction.
Similarly, SP<sub>i</sub>  - (CP<sub>i</sub>  - (SP<sub>i-1</sub>  - CP<sub>i-2</sub> -(.....-(SP<sub>1</sub>  - (CP<sub>1</sub>  - (SP<sub>0</sub>  - CP<sub>0</sub> )))))) is the overall profit for the i<sup>th</sup> transaction.

Therefore, the recurrent relation for the i<sup>th</sup> cost price can be written as :
CP<sub>i</sub> = CP<sub>i</sub> - Profit<sub>i-1</sub>
and the recurrent relation for profit for ith transaction can be written as :
Profit<sub>i</sub> = SP<sub>i</sub> - CP<sub>i</sub>

So here's what we'll do, maintain two arrays cost and profit, where cost[i] will store the minimum cost price of the stock for the i<sup>th</sup> transaction, and profit[i] will store the maximum profit for the i<sup>th</sup> transaction.

Code : 
