solutions.content:
```
class Solution {

    public int maxProfit(int k, int[] prices) {
        //return maxProfitInCubicTimeAndQuadraticSpace(k, prices);
        //return maxProfitInQuadraticTimeAndQuadraticSpace(k, prices);
        return maxProfitInQuadraticTimeAndLinearSpace(k, prices);
    }

    /*
        Approach - For a situation where k>n/2, it effectively means you can do any number of transactions 
        so, follow the usual approach of buying and selling. For cases where k<=n/2, Think DP. 

        Let's say f(i,j) is the profit with doing at most j transactions until day i.
        If you have to calculate f(i, j), thinking logically, there could be two possibilities :-
        1. You don't sell/buy anything on this day, i.e. by day number i-1, you have already completed j 
        transactions. You can quantify this by saying, "The profit I got by doing at most j transactions by 
        day number i-1". As a function that means f(i-1, j).
        2. You sold the last share on the ith day, thereby completing j transactions on the ith day. However,
        that would mean that you would have bought that share sometime earlier. Let's say you bought that on 
        day number m. Then you can quantify this by saying, "The profit I got by doing j-1 transctions until 
        mth day, then buying a share on the mth day and selling it on the ith day". The reason for "j-1 
        transactions until the mth day" is that you're allowed to be in the middle of any one buy/sell cycle.
        So if you bought your jth transaction on mth day, you should have sold your (j-1)th transaction on the 
        mth day before buying the jth transaction. Now as a function this will have 3 components :-
            i) f(m, j-1) = Profit achieved by doing at most (j-1) transactions until day m.
            ii) -prices[m] = Because you bought on mth day, so your profit decreases by prices[m], i.e.
                the price of the stock on mth day. Thus -prices[m].
            iii) +prices[i] = Since you're selling on ith day so you add prices[i] to your profit, i.e. the 
                price of the stock on ith day.

        Combined it becomes f(m, j-1)-prices[m]+prices[i]. Now we assumed that we bought on mth day. This can
        actually be any day before ith day. Since we have to maximize our profit, so we take :-
        MAX(f(m, j-1)-prices[m]+prices[i]), for 0<m<i.

        Our formula then becomes :-
        f(i,j) = MAX(f(i-1, j), MAX(f(m, j-1)-prices[m]+prices[i])) where 0<m<i.

        This is applied using a usual DP solution. Time Complexity is O(n^2) is for the i,j traversal, and 
        another linear search to find MAX(f(m, j-1)-prices[m]+prices[i]) where we traverse all
        values for m where 0<m<i;

        Thus TimeComplexity - O(n^3). Space Complexity - O(n^2);
    */
    public int maxProfitInCubicTimeAndQuadraticSpace(int k, int[] prices) {
        int n = prices.length;
        if(n<=0)return 0;
        if(k>n/2){
            int buy = -prices[0], sell=0, afterBuy=0, afterSell=0;
            for(int i=1;i<n;i++){
                afterSell = Math.max(sell, buy+prices[i]);
                afterBuy = Math.max(buy, sell-prices[i]);
                sell = afterSell;
                buy = afterBuy;
            }
            return afterSell;
        }
        int dp[][] = new int [n+1][k+1];
        for(int i=0;i<=n;i++)dp[i][0]=0;
        for(int i=0;i<=k;i++)dp[0][i]=0;

        for(int i=1;i<n;i++){
            for(int j=1;j<=k;j++){
                for (int m=0;m<i;m++){
                    dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i][j], Math.max(dp[i-1][j], dp[m][j-1]-prices[m]+prices[i]));
                }
            }
        }

        return dp[n-1][k];
    }

    /*
        The above approach gets accepted but it very slow. How can we optimize it? Let's look at the second 
        part of our expression, i.e. MAX(f(m, j-1)-prices[m]+prices[i]). This can be written as 
        prices[i]+MAX(f(m, j-1)-prices[m]). Technically, we're running a linear search to find the max value 
        of the expression inside the parentheses. 
        But we don't need that. m is effectively different values of i. We're already running a loop for i, 
        why can't we just keep track of the maximum value of f(i, j-1)-prices[i] encountered so far? 
        And then when the next value of i is assigned, max the new value of this expression with the old one. 
        This means that at every iteration of i, we can calculate prices[i]+MAX(f(m, j-1)-prices[m]) in 
        constant time. That removes the need for linear search and hence reduces time complexity to O(n^2).

        Time Complexity - O(n^2) Space Complexity - O(n^2)
    */

    public int maxProfitInQuadraticTimeAndQuadraticSpace(int k, int[] prices) {
        int n = prices.length;
        if(n<=1)return 0;
        if(k>n/2){
            int buy = -prices[0], sell=0, afterBuy=0, afterSell=0;
            for(int i=1;i<n;i++){
                afterSell = Math.max(sell, buy+prices[i]);
                afterBuy = Math.max(buy, sell-prices[i]);
                sell = afterSell;
                buy = afterBuy;
            }
            return afterSell;
        }
        int dp[][] = new int [n+1][k+1];
        for(int i=0;i<=n;i++)dp[i][0]=0;
        for(int i=0;i<=k;i++)dp[0][i]=0;

        for(int j=1;j<=k;j++){
            int state = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
            for(int i=1;i<n;i++){    
                state = Math.max(state, dp[i-1][j-1]-prices[i-1]);
                dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i][j], Math.max(dp[i-1][j], state+prices[i]));
            }
        }

        return dp[n-1][k];
    }

    /*
        The above solution optimized for time but the amount of space that we take is still huge. We can 
        notice that any time, for calculating f(i,j) all we need is values of (i-1) and (j-1). That would
        mean that for our dp[][] array, we only ever require two columns - column j and column j-1. i-1 is in
        the same column as i so nothing special required there.

        Thus we keep two columns instead of a grid - prev and curr. prev is to denote j-1 column and curr is
        to denote j column. Then we just repeat what we did in the above function

        Time Complexity - O(n^2) Space Complexity - O(n);
    */
    public int maxProfitInQuadraticTimeAndLinearSpace(int k, int[] prices) {
        int n = prices.length;
        if(n<=1)return 0;
        if(k>n/2){
            int buy = -prices[0], sell=0, afterBuy=0, afterSell=0;
            for(int i=1;i<n;i++){
                afterSell = Math.max(sell, buy+prices[i]);
                afterBuy = Math.max(buy, sell-prices[i]);
                sell = afterSell;
                buy = afterBuy;
            }
            return afterSell;
        }
        int prev [] = new int [n];
        int curr [] = new int [n];

        for(int j=1;j<=k;j++){
            int state = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
            prev = Arrays.copyOf(curr,curr.length);
            Arrays.fill(curr, 0);
            for(int i=1;i<n;i++){
                state = Math.max(state, prev[i-1]-prices[i-1]);
                curr[i] = Math.max(curr[i], Math.max(curr[i-1], state+prices[i]));
            }
        }
        return curr[n-1];
    }
}
```

