**Solution #1 - Recursion - Time Limit Exceeded**
1. Recursively find the max profit we can get in k transactions. The idea is to start at each index and if a price exists where we can make money by subtracting from our initial index AND we can still perform some transactions `k > 0`, then try it. 
2. It is possible that during our recursive calls while calculating `v1` that we find a max that isn't at the end, so we keep track of the max we have seen with Math.max() function.

```
class Solution {
    public int maxProfit(int k, int[] prices) {
        return rec(prices, 0, k);
    }
    public int rec(int[] prices, int idx, int k) {
        if(idx == prices.length) 
            return 0;

        int v1 = 0;
        for(int i = idx+1; i < prices.length; i++) {
            if(prices[idx] < prices[i] && k > 0) 
                v1 = Math.max(v1, rec(prices, i+1, k-1) + prices[i]-prices[idx]);
        }
        int v2 = rec(prices, idx+1, k);

        return Math.max(v1, v2);
    }
}
```

**Solution #2 - Recursion with Memoization - Accepted**
1. Same idea as before but we can store saved results into our dp table for fast lookups. 
2. The two factors that are changing throughout our process our the current index we are on (**idx**) and **k**, so those are the two values we are going to keep track of when storing and looking up values.
3. We add a quicksolve for larger sets where our memory limit would get time limit exceeded and the solution is accepted.

```
class Solution {
    public int maxProfit(int k, int[] prices) {
        int n = prices.length;
        if(k >= n/2) return quick(prices);

        return rec(prices, 0, k, new Integer[k+1][n]);
    }
    public int rec(int[] prices, int idx, int k, Integer[][] dp) {
        if(idx == prices.length) 
            return 0;
        if(dp[k][idx] != null)
            return dp[k][idx];

        int v1 = 0;
        for(int i = idx+1; i < prices.length; i++) {
            if(prices[idx] < prices[i] && k > 0) 
                v1 = Math.max(v1, rec(prices, i+1, k-1, dp) + prices[i]-prices[idx]);
        }
        int v2 = rec(prices, idx+1, k, dp);

        return dp[k][idx] = Math.max(v1, v2);
    }
    public int quick(int[] prices) {
        int res = 0;
        for(int i = 1; i < prices.length; i++)
            if(prices[i] > prices[i-1]) res += prices[i]-prices[i-1];
        return res;
    }
}
```

**Solution #3 - Bottom-Up Dynammic Programming - Accepted**
1. The idea is similar to our other solutions but here instead of using recursion to check all the possible prices we can iteratively build up our dp table which will lead us to the correct final answer.
2. I think this pretty much explains itself but the biggest and most confusing aspect of this specific algorithm is `max = Math.max(max, prev[j-1]-prices[j-1]);`. What is going on here is we are optimizing our buy for each price, given what we computed for previous `k` values. 
3. Once we have our max, we can check it based on our previously computed max, or value at `dp[i][j]` to see if we can need to carry over the old max, or create a new one. `dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i][j-1], max + prices[j]);` is saying if sell at prices[j] is this a new max profit?


```
class Solution {
    public int maxProfit(int k, int[] prices) {
        int n = prices.length;
        if(k >= n/2) return quick(prices);

        int[][] dp = new int[k+1][n];

        for(int i = 1; i <= k; i++) {
            int max = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
            for(int j = 1; j < n; j++) {
                max = Math.max(max, dp[i-1][j-1]-prices[j-1]);    // max so far if we buy at this price
                dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i][j-1], max + prices[j]); // max if we sell at prices[j]
            }
        }
        return dp[k][n-1];
    }
    public int quick(int[] prices) {
        int res = 0;
        for(int i = 1; i < prices.length; i++)
            if(prices[i] > prices[i-1]) res += prices[i]-prices[i-1];
        return res;
    }
}
```

**Solution #4 - Bottom-Up Dynammic Programming, Space Optimized - Accepted**
1. We saw in our last solution that at most, we are only looking back 1, step. When this is the case in dynammic programming problems we can always using two arrays to look what was previously used to calculate our new max profit. You can name them whatever you like, but for me, I like to use `prev` and `curr` because it helps me keep track of where I am, and which array I need to look at.
2. This is pretty much identical to our 2d dp solution but we swap the prev and curr array at each iteration accordingly.

```
class Solution {
    public int maxProfit(int k, int[] prices) {
        int n = prices.length;
        if(k >= n/2) return quick(prices);

        int[] prev = new int[n];

        for(int i = 1; i <= k; i++) {
            int max = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
            int[] curr = new int[n];
            for(int j = 1; j < n; j++) {
                max = Math.max(max, prev[j-1]-prices[j-1]);    // max so far if we buy at this price
                curr[j] = Math.max(curr[j-1], max + prices[j]); // max if we sell at prices[j]
            }
            prev = curr;
        }
        return prev[n-1];
    }
    public int quick(int[] prices) {
        int res = 0;
        for(int i = 1; i < prices.length; i++)
            if(prices[i] > prices[i-1]) res += prices[i]-prices[i-1];
        return res;
    }
}
```

A lot of times with these dynammic programming solutions I only see writeups on the optimized dp code and I always like to see how you build them out from a brute force recursive example, to an optimized one. Especially in interviews they are going to want to know the recurrence relationship and how you got to an optimized version so have an idea of how you came to the final solution is important.

