A lot discussions for this question are still super hard to understand, and one reason is that people swapped the i and j index, which commonly i should stand for the array index. Hope my explanation should be more clear and easier. 

dp[i,j]: i stands for the array index, i.e. the date, and the j stands for the the up to j transactions. One question at the very first thought, how can we deal with the notion of **at most**? Very easy, just refer to how we deal with the longest subsequence etc., that is, to let table[i] = table[i-1] as the initial value before the optimial induction. 

Based on the observation above, we can have the following induction. 
- at the date i and up to j transactions, we can just not transact the jth transaction, so we have the dp[i,j] = dp[i, j-1] as the initial value 
- what if we need to transact this jth transaction? As per the nature of DP's top-down characteristics, the thing can happen on the ith day can only be a sell. As we should not have any transactions overlapped, there must be a date p before i that we buy, and between p+1 and i-1 there should not be any transaction any more. Therefore, the dp[i,j] is equal to, the price[i] that we sell, minors the price[p] that we buy, and the profit we already obtained on the p-1 day with at most j-1 times transaction. 
- In order to reduce the time complexity, we dont have to loop repeatedly. Instead, we can use a greedy idea here, that we record the min value of (price[p]- dp[p-1, j-1]), because this min value can guarantee the profit on  dp[p-1, j-1] for sure is max 

```
  public int maxProfit(int k, int[] prices) {
    int len = prices.length;
    if (k >= len / 2)
      return greedy(prices);

    int[][] dp = new int[len][k+1];
    for (int j = 1; j <= k; j++) {
      int prevMinProfit = prices[0];
      for (int i = 1; i < len; i++) {
        dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i-1][j], prices[i] - prevMinProfit);
        prevMinProfit = Math.min(prevMinProfit, prices[i] - dp[i - 1][j - 1]);
      }
    }
    return dp[len-1][k];
  }


  private int greedy(int[] prices) {
    int len = prices.length, profit = 0;
    for (int i = 1; i < len; i++){
      if (prices[i] > prices[i - 1])
        profit += prices[i] - prices[i - 1];
    }
    return profit;
  }

```

