# SPACE OPTIMIZED SOLUTION 
# Approach
The function solvetab takes the prices vector and an integer k (maximum allowed transactions) as input.

Initialize two 1D vectors curr and next, each with a size of 2*k+1. These vectors will be used to store the maximum profit for different scenarios. curr[op] represents the maximum profit at the current day with op indicating the number of operations (buy and sell transactions) performed so far.

The outer loop runs from n-1 to 0, iterating backward through the prices array. This helps us build the curr and next vectors from the last day to the first day.

Within the outer loop, there is a nested loop that runs from 0 to 2*k-1. This loop handles all possible scenarios for the number of operations performed at each day (both buying and selling).

For each index (current day) and op (number of operations), calculate the maximum profit for the current day and operation scenario:

If op is even, it means a buying operation is allowed, so we consider two options:
a. Perform the buying operation on the current day and move to the next operation (op+1), considering the profit obtained by subtracting the stock price from the result of the next day's calculation with the same number of allowed transactions (next[op+1]).
b. Skip the buying operation and move to the next operation (op), considering the profit obtained from the next day's calculation with the same number of allowed transactions (next[op]).
If op is odd, it means a selling operation is allowed, so we consider two options:
a. Perform the selling operation on the current day and move to the next operation (op+1), considering the profit obtained by adding the stock price to the result of the next day's calculation with the same number of allowed transactions (next[op+1]).
b. Skip the selling operation and move to the next operation (op), considering the profit obtained from the next day's calculation with the same number of allowed transactions (next[op]).
Update the curr[op] value with the calculated maximum profit for the current index and op.

After filling the curr vector for the current day, copy its values to the next vector. This is done to update the values for the next day in the next iteration.

Once the loops are completed, the answer will be stored in next[0], which represents the maximum profit achievable with at most k transactions on the given array of stock prices.

Return next[0] as the maximum profit.
```
class Solution {
public:

int solvetab(vector<int>& prices,int k )
{
    int n = prices.size();
    vector<int>curr(2*k+1);
    vector<int>next(2*k+1);


    for(int index=n-1;index>=0;index--)
    {
        for(int op=0;op<2*k;op++)
        {
            int profit=0;
            if(op%2==0)
            {
                profit=max(-prices[index]+next[op+1] , 0 + next[op]); 
            }
            else
            {
                profit=max(prices[index]+ next[op+1], 0 + next[op]); 
            }
            curr[op]=profit;
            }
            next=curr;


    }
    return next[0];
}

    int maxProfit(int k, vector<int>& prices) {
        return solvetab(prices,k);
    }
};
