solutions.content:
The idea is to use state machine to keep track of every possible profit
For one transaction, we have two states: buying and selling
For every state: we could stay, or buying/selling, but we should choose the maximum profit way
For buying: we will pay stock price so profit -= stock price from last selling state
For selling: we will earn money so profit += stock price from last buying state
For rest: we remain same profit

One special case is that when k > prices.length / 2, in this case we could consider only prices.length / 2 possible transactions. ( K is so large that we could consider as unlimited transactions)

```
class Solution {
  public int maxProfit(int k, int[] prices) {
    if (k == 0 || prices.length == 0 || prices.length == 1) {
      return 0;
    }
    k = Math.min(k, prices.length / 2);
    int[] states = new int[k * 2];
    for (int i = 0; i < states.length; i++) {
      states[i] = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
    }
    for (int i = 0; i < prices.length; i++) {
      states[0] = Math.max(states[0], -prices[i]);
      for (int j = 1; j < states.length; j++) {
        if (j % 2 == 0) {
          states[j]= Math.max(states[j], states[j - 1] - prices[i]);
        } else {
          states[j] = Math.max(states[j], states[j - 1] + prices[i]);
        }
      }
    }
    return Math.max(states[k * 2 - 1], 0);
  }
}
```

