I just like to present another idea of DP solution, which I didn't find yet in the Discuss. 

Transaction is defined as two operations (buy and sell). And the question has a constraint that "buy must precede the sell" and "no multiple transactions can be engaged at one day". To take advantage of this constraint, We can model the question as a finite state machine. 

![image](https://s3-lc-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/users/heronalps/image_1523144222.png)

The transaction function follows:

Hold[i] = Max(Hold[i], Sold[i - 1] - prices[i])
Sold[i] = Max(Sold[i], Hold[i - 1] + prices[i])

dp[i][Hold] equals to the max profit upon i day by holding the stock at the end.
dp[i][Sold] equals to the max profit upon i day by selling the stock at the end.

Let's take an example: [2, ,7, 3, 1, 5, 8, 9, 4, 13], 2. The dp array should be constructed like this at day 3:

![image](https://s3-lc-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/users/heronalps/image_1523145107.png)

Every time a new price comes in play, we enlarge the dp array row-wise with two negative infinity and calculate backwards up to first operation. The dp array is updated at day 4 to the below:

![image](https://s3-lc-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/users/heronalps/image_1523145341.png)

Notice that the operation sequence has to be checkered, so odd operations could only be Hold and even operations can only be Sold. The final max profit must be within Sold column, which will be returned at the end. 

As what the common solutions do, this one gets TLE without using pruning trick. The worst runtime is O(n * k). 

Happy coding!


	public int maxProfit(int k, int[] prices) {
	    if (k >= prices.length / 2) return max(prices);

        int rows = Math.min(2 * k, prices.length);
        int[][] dp = new int[rows + 1][2];
        dp[0][0] = dp[0][1] = 0;
        int max = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < prices.length; i++) {
            for (int j = Math.min(rows, i + 1); j >= 1; j--) {
                if (i + 1 <= rows && j == Math.min(rows, i + 1)) {
                    dp[j][0] = dp[j][1] = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
                }
                if (j % 2 == 1) {
                    dp[j][0] = Math.max(dp[j][0], dp[j - 1][1] - prices[i]);
                } 
                else {
                    dp[j][1] = Math.max(dp[j][1], dp[j - 1][0] + prices[i]);
                    max = Math.max(max, dp[j][1]);
                }
            }
        }
        return max;
    }
    private int max(int[] prices) {
        int sum = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i < prices.length; i++) {
            if (prices[i] > prices[i - 1]) {
                sum += prices[i] - prices[i - 1];
            }
        }
        return sum;
    }

