# Intuition
Stock selling problem always reminds me the concept of DP.

# Approach
In the question it is clearly given that you can buy and sell the stocks multiple times but there are limited transactions possible.

So we take two things into consideration. 
1) Whether a stock is bought.
2) Transactions left.

Let us make a flag variable which determines whether we hold a stock. If we hold the stock flag is 1 else it is 0. 

If we do not hold a stack, we have two ways either buy the stock or just do not buy. We need to pick the maximum from both the cases. In the case considering that you buy the stock update the flag as 1 and subtract 1 from Transactions Left as one of the transaction is done for buying. As you buy the stoct your money is debited so we subtract the money. In the case considering that you donot buy the stock update nothing.

If we do hold a stack, we have two ways either sell the stock or just do not sell. We need to pick the maximum from both the cases. In the case considering that you sell the stock update the flag as 0 and subtract 1 from Transactions Left as one of the transaction is done for selling. As you sell the stoct your money is credited so we add the money. In the case considering that you donot sell the stock update nothing.

The terminating Case would be either index is greater than size or no transactions left.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(N*K);

- Space complexity:
O(N*K);

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
int soln(vector<int>&prices,int idx,int transactionsleft,int flag, vector<vector<vector<int>>>&dp){
    if(idx>=prices.size() || (transactionsleft == 0)){
        return 0;
    }
    if(dp[idx][transactionsleft][flag] != -1){
        return dp[idx][transactionsleft][flag];
    }
    int ans = INT_MIN;
    if(flag){
        ans = max(ans,soln(prices,idx+1,transactionsleft-1,0,dp)+prices[idx]);
        ans = max(ans,soln(prices,idx+1,transactionsleft,1,dp));
    }else{
        ans = max(ans,soln(prices,idx+1,transactionsleft-1,1,dp)-prices[idx]);
        ans = max(ans,soln(prices,idx+1,transactionsleft,0,dp));
    }
    return dp[idx][transactionsleft][flag] = ans;
}
    int maxProfit(int k, vector<int>& prices) {
       vector<vector<vector<int>>>dp(prices.size(),vector<vector<int>>(2*k+1,vector<int>(2,-1)));
       return soln(prices,0,2*k,0,dp);
    }
};
```

